If `damon_sysfs_handle_cmd` calls `damos_walk`, and all schemes are deactivated due to watermarks, `damos_walk` waits forever on `control->completion`. Meanwhile, `state_store` *still* holds the `damon_sysfs_lock`. This effectively freezes the entire DAMON sysfs interface, because anything else trying to use a sysfs call will block on `damon_sysfs_lock` with `-EBUSY`. Even though `state_store` uses `mutex_trylock`, that `-EBUSY` just means the interface is blocked for other uses.

I traced the code execution, and even if there are schemes, but none are ready to apply based on their `next_apply_sis` value, `kdamond_apply_schemes` won't complete the walk. It will increment `passed_sample_intervals` every iteration and eventually, `has_schemes_to_apply` will be true. That is fine, and by design. However, if ALL schemes are deactivated due to watermarks, it *will* call `damos_walk_cancel()`.

So, it's not a permanent deadlock when all watermarks prevent applications from running, as `kdamond_wait_activation()` will call `damos_walk_cancel()`, and the `damos_walk` call will be completed. But if the schemes are configured with large `apply_interval_us`, this will block for that period. Given `damos_walk` is called inside `state_store` while holding `damon_sysfs_lock`, this will be a DoS against the DAMON subsystem. The fix doesn't really address this, it addresses a separate deadlock that occurs in the case where the DAMON thread exits and a walk is in progress, as the walk will never complete.

